title: For Sale/Trade:  Dreyse Model 1907
postcontent:
Hi looking to see what offers are out there for a 1907 Dreyse.  I don't have any history on this gun other that what I have been able to research as it was left in the house when I bought it.  In discussions with a what I believe to be expert on this gun, he says the first 700 or so went to the police in Prussia and had the serial number on the side like this one has.  It does not have the original grips though.  But the holster and two magazines are desirable to some.  He also tells me it was probably used in WWI, and possibly WWII--most of the ones over here were captured in one of the two world wars, especially the ones in holsters like this one.  

It shoots standard .32 ACP, which was known in Europe as the 7.65mm Browning.

I am not committed to selling or trading as it is a piece of history, but for the right offer I might be.  I am not interested in anything less than $450 or valued less than that as I have a current offer for that.  

It is not in perfect condition and I cannot tell you if it actually works or not as I have not shot it...ammo that is with it seems very old. 

More info can be found at this website: http://unblinkingeye.com/Guns/07Dreyse/07dreyse.html

Comes with the gun, holster, two mags and the old ammo.  I will not sell the pieces individually.  

Thanks for looking

title: For Sale:  New Proposed Armslist Legislation--Please read carefully.
location: Charlotte and all surrounding areas., Charlotte, North Carolina
postcontent:
New Proposed Armslist Etiquette (Just blowing off some steam, laugh with me).
Some of you are already in compliance.  If so, please disregard this update.  If you are not in compliance, please take a few minutes to familiarize yourself with how things work around here.

Because of the varied levels of confusion and miscommunication on this site regarding transactions, I just wanted to take a moment to suggest some rules for making sure everyone has an enjoyable productive experience on this site.  Proposed etiquette rules are as follows:

If you are a seller:

1) You are correct in assuming that you are the superior being in the transaction.  You are doing your fellow man a service and favor by offering your personal belongings up for sale.  Sellers should feel lucky to even receive a return email from you, much less actually engage in negotiations or transactions.

2) Because you are selling an item or items, you are also correct in assuming that the value of said item far exceeds the value that would be assigned in a retail store, pawn shop, or any other public or private market.  Its not ultra-valuable because of what it is, it is ultra-valuable because you’re selling it and you want the most money you can get for it.

3) Even if you have no intention of selling your item or items, and your Blue Book of Gun Values is more than four or five feet away from you, feel free to list your item anyway, making sure to indicate “make offer,” and/or “I’m just seeing what’s out there.”

(This reinforces the superiority of the seller as indicated in Rule #1.  It lets would be buyers know that you do not value money, or time, as you clearly have an abundance of both.)

4)  Referencing Rule #3, you can surely use the “make offer” price to see what people will pay for an item you actually want to sell.  Upon using this feature, feel free to respond to reasonable and low ball offers by becoming “butt hurt,” as you did not indicate the ballpark of what you might want to get out of the item.

5)  Upon becoming “butt hurt,” feel free to employ one of the following methods to cope with the emotional trauma of being so utterly disrespected:
	A. Completely ignore the offer, and do not, under any circumstances                 counter-offer.  This may lead to price negotiations. 
	B.  If you find yourself in the terrifying grips of negotiations somehow, reply with one or two word email/text responses, or more verbose, vague responses.  Be rude.  “Nope,” “Looking for more,” and “I’m not sure how much I’d like to sell it for” are all acceptable 	and recommended responses.  

These methods, if properly employed will achieve your ultimate goal of preventing a sale.

Remember, if you sell something, you may then take that money and spend it—This could possibly stimulate the economy:  Something which cannot happen, as Barack Obama will take credit for it.

6)  In the event you do sell something, don’t take your listing down.  In fact, bump the listing as much as you can.  This creates the confusion and frustration that Armslist is all about.

If you are a buyer:  

1)  Remember, Armslist is just like Walmart: you can browse, go to the bathroom, and complain about the ever rising costs of things.  

2)  You should email buyers in one of several ways.  Use whichever is most convenient:
	A.  “I only have 60% of your asking price.  Is that ok?”
	B. “ Will you take (insert lowball offer equivalent to half of what a pawn shop would give).”
	C.  “Do you still have it?” (This is potentially ok, referencing Rule 6 under buyers)
	D.  “I live two and a half hours away—you think you can drive to me?”

*Combining 2A and 2D is particularly effective—however it takes a master negotiator to pull this off.

3)  If the seller messes up and responds to your email with something resembling actual negotiation, you should under no circumstances respond in any meaningful way.  At best, you can ignore him/her completely.  If this is impossible, simply use the “buyer communication methods” found under Rule 5, Section B.  However, employing Rule 5, Section B is undesirable, as you may accidenty find yourself successfully negotiating.  

4)  Just like Walmart, you can commit to buying things, and then just leave your cart at checkout.  This is achieved in the armslist world by somehow getting a seller to negotiate and agree on a price, only to be saved from a sale by you not showing up.  While the buyer knows he is the superior being, you “stick it to him and show him who’s boss” by not meeting or showing up at a prescribed time and place.  Do not be tempted to show up because the buyer has lured you with "a good price," and a "convenient location."

*Remember, as a buyer it is not your job to buy anything, only to waste the time of the seller and annoy him.  This is the male version of “retail therapy” that many women enjoy as they run salespeople around and try things on, only to say they’ll “think about it” and not buy anything.  

If you are a trader, things become more difficult.  You must use the rules of both the buyer and seller while avoiding a successful transaction at all costs.  For the novice trader, keep in mind that even if you and the other trader have comparable items, your items are far superior and higher in value, while his trading items must be regarded as having the same value as petting zoo feces.  I hope this helps.
